Hi,
We have a problem with relations between particular spans.
I my scenario a tracing consists of 3 spans: 2 CLIENT kind, 1 SERVER kind.

Calls tree looks like that: 1 client span (id=74a5bdd765145dd2) -->  2 client span (id=76b8e4cf36177665, parent=74a5bdd765145dd2) -->  3 server span (id=d6762f661eb4de16, parent=76b8e4cf36177665).

In Zipking server, spans are presented correctly whilst in Skywalking, CLIENT spans are not connected to each other.
root --> 1 client span (id=74a5bdd765145dd2)
root --> 2 client span (id=76b8e4cf36177665, parent=74a5bdd765145dd2) --> 3 server span (id=d6762f661eb4de16, parent=76b8e4cf36177665)
 
I believe I found a suspicious piece of code. In `org.apache.skywalking.oap.server.receiver.zipkin.analysis.transform.SegmentBuilder#initSpan`
there is a switch which assumes that there might be built a reference only when  **SERVER** span arrives:
```
 switch (kind) {
            case CLIENT:
                spanBuilder.setSpanType(SpanType.Exit);
                String peer = getPeer(parentSpan, span);
                if (peer != null) {
                    spanBuilder.setPeer(peer);
                }
                clientSideSpan = new ClientSideSpan(span, spanBuilder);
                clientPartSpan.put(span.id(), clientSideSpan);
                break;
            case SERVER:
                spanBuilder.setSpanType(SpanType.Entry);
                this.buildRef(spanBuilder, span, parentSegmentSpan, parentSpan);
                break;
            case CONSUMER:
                spanBuilder.setSpanType(SpanType.Entry);
                this.buildRef(spanBuilder, span, parentSegmentSpan, parentSpan);
                break;
            case PRODUCER:
                spanBuilder.setSpanType(SpanType.Exit);
                peer = getPeer(parentSpan, span);
                if (peer != null) {
                    spanBuilder.setPeer(peer);
                }
                clientSideSpan = new ClientSideSpan(span, spanBuilder);
                clientPartSpan.put(span.id(), clientSideSpan);
                break;
            default:
                spanBuilder.setSpanType(SpanType.Local);
        }
```
